g.text: (Hover over nodes to see descriptions of kinds
of linear operators, and some of their properties)
Can include entries with infinite magnitude.
Magnitudes can be any non-nagtive real number.
Representable in QAL, but not always transparently displayable.
All magnitudes less than a fixed finite positive real number.
Transparently displayable in QAL (e.g., magnitudes linearly mapped to lightness in HSL colors).
All rows and colums have entries with nonnegative magnitude and the magnitudes sum to 1.

Extreme points of Birkhof polytope (which is the set of all bistochastic matrices.
Convex hull of permutation matrices, i.e., convex combinations of permutation matrices,
which is a proper subset of the set of all linear combinations of permutations matrices [all finite matrices?]).
Two matrix representations are possible: Column representation (used in QAL. May change later for CCDs and "pulling weave"), and row representation.
Most relevant to quantum theory and thus to QAL.
Invertible (inverse exists) and inverse is adjoint (conjugate transpose).
A unitary is the imaginary exponential of some Hermitian U=exp(iH).
Complex analog of orthogonal real matrices.
Self-adjoint (matrix is equal to its conjugate transpose/adjoint).
Complex analog of symmetric real matrices.
Entries can be zero or one only (binary).
Magnitudes take only nonnegative integer values. No phases.
